oncerns around the potential impact, Ministers also decided to delay the implementation of Section 18(3) of the Care Act 2014 until 2020 in line with the timetable for implementing funding reform. This will allow the Department enough time to research the likely impact of these reforms on the market and develop effective mitigations.</p><p>Information on the number of delayed transfers of care is published by NHS England on a monthly basis and is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/delayed-transfers-of-care/delayed-transfers-of-care-data-2015-16/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/delayed-transfers-of-care/delayed-transfers-of-care-data-2015-16/</a></p><p>- see the delayed days by responsible organisation spreadsheet.</p><p>We do not have centrally held figures regarding the numbers of people who will enter the social care system in future, any impact that the cap on care costs might have on delayed transfers of care, or the numbers of people who might have asked local authorities to arrange their care under s18(3) of the Care Act 2014.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","31810 ; 32038 ; 32040","2016-03-24T10:23:16.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483184/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483184/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-21","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department plans to (a) introduce the appeals system set out in Section 72 of the Care Act 2014 and (b) revise the current care capital limits.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","32039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483185","Home Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Home Office has not received any representations from the North Wales Police and Crime Commissioner on the removal of people convicted of child abuse and rape from the sex offenders’ register.</p><p>Offenders who are on the register indefinitely are only able to seek a police review after 15 years. In 2012, the Home Office issued detailed guidance to police forces on assessing applications for review. All decisions to release a sex offender from the notification requirements must be authorised by a senior police officer. Public safety is at the heart of all decisions taken by police, and those who continue to pose a risk will remain on the sex offenders' register, if necessary for life.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-24T13:31:40.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483185/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483185/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-21","Violent and Sex Offender Register: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received from the North Wales Police and Crime Commissioner on the removal of people convicted of child abuse and rape from the Sex Offenders Register.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","32030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483186","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-31","<p>The EU has two mechanisms for freezing the assets of individuals and groups suspected of involvement in terrorism. The UN’s ISIL (Daesh) and Al-Qaida sanctions regime is implemented in the United Kingdom by way of EU Council Regulation (EC) No. 881/2002 and subsequent EU regulations adding new individuals and entities to the regime. The EU also has its own autonomous counter-terrorism regime under Common Position 931, for listing individuals and groups based on national competent authority decisions by a Member State or third country.</p><p>HM Treasury reports quarterly to Parliament on the implementation of these measures. The Treasury’s latest report [http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-02-24/HCWS548/], published on 24 February 2016, sets out that in Q4 of 2015 a total of 43 UK accounts were frozen under either EU or UN counter-terrorism measures. A further 36 accounts were frozen under the UK’s domestic Terrorist Asset Freezing etc. Act 2010 regime.</p><p>The EU’s autonomous regime lends a multiplying effect to the reach of a number of the UK’s domestic asset freezes and proscriptions of terrorist organisations, and facilitates the sharing of information on designated persons between Member States. The UK also benefits from the consistent application across EU territory of the UN’s ISIL (Daesh) and Al-Qaida asset freezes.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-31T15:46:48.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483186/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483186/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-21","Terrorism: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what powers the EU has to freeze the assets of suspected terrorist groups or individuals suspected of involvement in terrorism; and what assessment he has made of the benefits to the UK of those powers.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","32019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483187","Home Office","false","2016-03-30","<p>The National Crime Agency (NCA) is a non-ministerial government department, however it is accountable to Parliament via the Home Secretary. As such I have contacted the NCA to inform my answer to you.</p><p>During the course of cyber-dependent crime operations over the last five years (including SOCA Cyber and Metropolitan Police Central e-Crime Unit led operations) and based on recorded data following a subject's arrest we are unable to determine the level of involvement of autistic individuals in cybercrime offences, or the level of vulnerability of individuals on the autism spectrum to various other aspects of cyber crime.</p><p>The NCA are now embarking on research in partnership with Academia, Private Industry and Special Interest groups to explore the possibility of links between Autism and cyber-dependent crime. Understanding gained from this research will inform the NCA on best practice for managing operations and educational Prevent activity.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","32017","2016-03-30T14:08:59.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483187/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483187/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-21","Cybercrime: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the level of vulnerability of people on the autism spectrum to various aspects of cybercrime.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","32018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483188","Home Office","false","2016-03-30","<p>The National Crime Agency (NCA) is a non-ministerial government department, however it is accountable to Parliament via the Home Secretary. As such I have contacted the NCA to inform my answer to you.</p><p>During the course of cyber-dependent crime operations over the last five years (including SOCA Cyber and Metropolitan Police Central e-Crime Unit led operations) and based on recorded data following a subject's arrest we are unable to determine the level of involvement of autistic individuals in cybercrime offences, or the level of vulnerability of individuals on the autism spectrum to various other aspects of cyber crime.</p><p>The NCA are now embarking on research in partnership with Academia, Private Industry and Special Interest groups to explore the possibility of links between Autism and cyber-dependent crime. Understanding gained from this research will inform the NCA on best practice for managing operations and educational Prevent activity.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","32018","2016-03-30T14:08:59.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483188/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483188/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-21","Cybercrime: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the level of involvement of autistic people in cybercrime offences.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","32017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483189","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-29","<p>Alongside the conclusions of the February European Council, the European Commission made a separate Declaration on the emergency brake (the ‘Commission Declaration on the Safeguard Mechanism’). This Declaration set out the Commission’s view that the exceptional situation that the brake is intended to cover exists in the UK today.</p><p> </p><p>Additional details are a matter for the implementation of the proposal, and further announcements will be made in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-03-29T12:55:53.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483189/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483189/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483189/answer/previousversion/53605","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-21","Migration: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will provide an estimate of (a) the total level of immigration from other EU member states and (b) the annual number of people coming to settle in the UK from other EU member states which would trigger the activation of the proposed alert and safeguard emergency brake mechanism; and what discussions he has had with his counterparts in other EU member states and the European Commission on the appropriate thresholds for the emergency brake mechanism to be activated.","false","Biography information for Sir William Cash","Stone","Sir William Cash","31955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483190","Home Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>We are strengthening data collection on human trafficking and other forms of modern slavery in several ways. In the Modern Slavery Act we introduced a duty on named public authorities to notify the Home Office every time they have reasonable grounds to believe they have encountered a victim of modern slavery.</p><p>These notifications can be anonymous so that data is collected even if the potential victim does not want to engage with the authorities. We are reviewing the National Referral Mechanism form, so that it better captures key data about potential victims and perpetrators. Polaris and Unseen UK are working with other NGOs and law enforcement to launch an enhanced modern slavery helpline later this year which will capture more data and help to shine a light on the scale and nature of this appalling crime.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-24T13:31:12.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483190/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483190/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-21","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken to strengthen its data collection strategy to help combat human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","31936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483191","Home Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>The cost of pre-departure accommodation is kept under review. The Home Office is currently considering the most cost-effective way of providing pre-departure accommodation within an enforced family returns service.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-24T13:33:01.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483191/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483191/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-21","Cedars Pre-departure Accommodation Facility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress her Department has made on plans for the future of the Cedars pre-departure accommodation site.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","31868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483192","Home Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>We expect to commence the Psychoactive Substances Act in its entirety in the spring. We need to ensure the readiness of all the activity necessary to enable the smooth implementation of the legislation across the UK and to support law enforcement in their ability to drive forward the legislation on commencement.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-03-24T13:31:24.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483192/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483192/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-21","Psychoactive Substances Act 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when those parts of the Psychoactive Substances Act 2016 which have not come into force are expected to come into force.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","32044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483193","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-30","<p>In the manifesto in April 2015 and in the UK Aid Strategy published in November 2015, we committed to help 60 million people get access to clean water and sanitation in support of goal 6 of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.</p><p> </p><p>We will achieve this target through projects managed by our Country Offices, through projects managed from the UK and through our contributions to multilateral organisations such as the World Bank. We will continue to invest in country and regional programmes to improve water resources management, water efficiency and improve water quality, as well as drive value for money.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-03-30T14:25:14.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483193/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483193/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-21","Developing Countries: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans the Government has to support efforts to achieve goal 6 of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development on water and sanitation.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","31973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483194","Department for International Development","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Budget document set out reductions to the Official Development Assistance budget of £650m in 2019/20 to reflect revised economic forecasts published by the Office for Budget Responsibility. As in the last Parliament, the government has and will continue to adapt spending plans to ensure the 0.7% target is met.</p><p>The allocation of ODA will be decided by HMG in due course, in line with the UK Aid Strategy, and taking into account the relative value for money of ODA programmes and strategic fit with HMG objectives.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-03-24T15:52:21.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483194/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483194/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-21","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the (a) effect of lower-than predicted growth rates on the Overseas Development Assistance budget and (b) implications of such rates on the budget for her Department.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","31950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483195","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-31","<p>The specific information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. We are committed to ensuring that prisoners have appropriate and early access to their legal representatives. Guidance to both prisons and legal practitioners on facilitating legal visits is published in Prison Service Instruction 16/2011.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-03-31T11:36:17.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483195/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483195/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Legal Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on the number of times that lawyers have not been able to meet their clients in custody in England and Wales at less than 12 hours' notice due to staff shortages, staff disputes or other administrative reasons in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many Crown or magistrates' court hearings have been adjourned or delayed as a result in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","32011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483196","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-31","<p>The Independent Monitoring Boards are supported by the IMB Secretariat, which is a small team of civil servants based in the Ministry of Justice. The Secretariat staff are involved in supporting the work of IMBs, the National Council and the IMB President, mainly through providing back-office administrative support. Funding for the IMBs is made from within the MoJ budget.</p><p> </p><p>The Prisons Minister considers each report and responds directly to the Chair of the relevant Board within the agreed eight week timeframe, providing comprehensive answers to any concerns raised for the Minister or the Justice Secretary’s specific attention.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-31T11:27:45.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483196/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483196/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Independent Monitoring Boards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on (a) support for independent monitoring boards and (b) consideration of the recommendations which those boards make in their annual reports to his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","32010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483197","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-24","<p>We are pleased the court confirmed that the Lord Chancellor did have the power to set domestic violence evidence requirements. We are carefully considering the judgment as we decide how best to respond to the court’s concerns and will make a further announcement in due course.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-24T17:44:10.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483197/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483197/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Legal Aid Scheme: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Court of Appeal's decision on domestic violence evidential requirements for legal aid, what interim steps his Department plans to make to allow victims of domestic violence with evidence of financial abuse access to legal aid.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","32031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483198","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-24","<p>The number of National Minimum Wage claims accepted by the Employment Tribunal in each of the last five years, including those accepted by the Tribunal since 1 July 2015, are published in the Tribunal and Gender Recognition Certificate Statistics Quarterly. The number of successful National Minimum Wage claims are also published in the quarterly statistics. The most recent report, for the period October to December 2015, published on 10 March 2016, can be viewed at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-and-gender-recognition-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-and-gender-recognition-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>The Tribunal only records and publishes awards made to claimants in discrimination cases. The amount awarded in National Minimum Wage claims in each of the last five years can only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information relating to the period of time an Employment Tribunal claim refers to underpayment of the National Minimum Wage for a period of more than (a) two and (b) six years is not recorded by the Tribunal and can only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","31873","2016-03-24T17:44:07.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483198/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483198/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many claims for underpayment of the national minimum wage have been brought before employment tribunals since 1 July 2015; and how many such claims referred to underpayment of the national minimum wage for a period of more than (a) two and (b) six years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","31952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483199","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-24","<p>The family courts take the issue of domestic violence extremely seriously. The Child Arrangement Programme and Practice Direction 12J set out a strong and clear framework where domestic violence is alleged and all judges receive specific training on this framework.</p><p> </p><p>In prisons the National Offenders Management Service accredited programmes are a proven way of tackling intimate partner violence and reducing reoffending in custody and the community. All programmes are based on the latest theory base and are regularly updated to make sure they continue to be as effective as possible. Provision of these services is widely available and provides an effective response to the causes of intimate partner violence.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-03-24T14:50:55.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483199/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483199/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of child deaths (a) by people who have been found guilty of and (b) related to domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","31933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483200","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-24","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-24T17:00:54.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483200/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483200/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Knives: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many online sellers of knives have been (a) prosecuted and (b) convicted under section 141A of the Criminal Justice Act 1988 for selling knives to people under 18 since that section came into force; and what sentences were handed down to people so convicted.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","31953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483201","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Government has discussed human rights reform with a range of stakeholders in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, including ministers in the Scottish and Welsh Governments and the Northern Ireland Executive.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to engage fully with the devolved administrations as we develop our proposals.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-24T12:29:20.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483201/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483201/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions he has held with his counterparts in the devolved administrations on proposals to repeal the Human Rights Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","31927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483202","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-24","<p>We will bring forward proposals for a Bill of Rights, which will replace the Human Rights Act. Our Bill will protect fundamental human rights, but also prevent their abuse and restore some common sense to the system. We will fully consult on our proposals before introducing legislation and will publish our proposals in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-24T12:40:00.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483202/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483202/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-21","Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to consult on proposals to repeal the Human Rights Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","31928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483203","Prime Minister","false","2016-03-24","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to ‘Sporting Future: A New Strategy for an Active Nation’, published in December 2015, a copy of which can be accessed on the gov.uk website.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-03-24T16:12:12.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483203/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483203/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-03-21","Sports: Departmental Coordination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if he will create a group at ministerial level of representatives from the relevant government departments to ensure that progress is made on the Government's sport strategy with cross-departmental coordination.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","31909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483204","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>A full list of transport projects (involving UK participants) that have been awarded funding from the Connecting Europe Facility is available on the Innovation and Networks Executive Agency web-site:</p><p><a href="https://ec.europa.eu/inea/en/connecting-europe-facility/cef-transport/projects-by-country/united-kingdom" target="_blank">https://ec.europa.eu/inea/en/connecting-europe-facility/cef-transport/projects-by-country/united-kingdom</a></p><p>The web-site includes an overview of the project, the participants, the implementation schedule and the amount of funding awarded.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-24T10:45:23.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483204/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483204/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Transport: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which projects in the UK will receive funding from the Connecting Europe Facility transport 2015 Multi-Annual Work Programme.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483205","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The information listed in the table below provides information for the last three complete calendar years:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Mobile Phones</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Tablets </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Government Procurement Cards (GPC*)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>140</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>226</p></td><td><p>120</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>670</p></td><td><p>263</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*HS2 Ltd does not have Corporate Credit Cards, it has Government Procurement Cards (in line with Government policy they have recently been renamed as Electronic Purchasing Card Solutions).</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-24T14:30:05.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483205/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483205/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many members of staff of HS2 Ltd have been provided with (a) mobile telephones, (b) tablet devices and (c) corporate credit cards in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483206","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>Government intends to deposit a hybrid Bill for HS2 from West Midlands to Crewe (HS2 Phase 2a) before the end of 2017. This will enable this section of route to open in 2027, six years earlier than originally planned. This means that cities across the North West and Scotland will realise more of the benefits of HS2 sooner.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-24T10:22:53.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483206/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483206/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to bring forward separate legislative proposals on the proposed extension of High Speed 2 from the West Midlands to Crewe.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483207","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The working assumption that the Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) is passed on to passengers 50% through lower fares and 50% through increased service levels was presented to and informally sense checked with industry members attending BSOG related working groups held by the Department over 2014 and early 2015.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T13:53:00.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483207/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483207/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 16 March 2016 to Question 30285, whether the working assumption that benefits from the Bus Service Operators Grant are passed on to passengers 50 per cent through lower fares and 50 per cent through increased service levels was informed by discussions with bus operators.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","31975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483208","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>There are 18 Natura 2000 sites within 10 miles of the proposed Phase 2 route. This is the route as proposed in the July 2013 route consultation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-24T10:54:33.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483208/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483208/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Natura 20000 sites are located within 10 miles of the proposed route of phase two of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483209","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Department for Transport was awarded €39.2 million for HS2 under the European Union’s Connecting Europe Facility to fund Ground Investigation works for Phase 1 of the High Speed 2 Programme. The EU has agreed to provide this funding in stages between 2015 and 2019.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-24T11:03:45.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483209/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483209/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much EU funding has been provided for ground investigations related to High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483210","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The actual competition impacts will depend on how franchising is implemented at the local level. The Department’s high level assessment of the potential competition impacts of the Buses Bill proposals will be set out in the Impact Assessment which will accompany the introduction of the Bill. Individual local authorities will be better placed to conduct a detailed competition assessment of any changes they propose to make to their local bus market in light of the Bill.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T13:47:53.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483210/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483210/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Bus Services: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the proposed Buses Bill, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on competition in the bus services market of bus operators retaining vehicle fleets, depots and other strategic assets when bus services are franchised.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","31972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483211","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Buses Bill will not specify the format in which the data on routes, timetables, punctuality and fares must be provided. The Bill would give the Secretary of State the powers to make secondary legislation to mandate the provision of data. The specific format of the data will be determined following discussions with industry in due course.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T13:26:15.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483211/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483211/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2016 to Question 29611, in what specified format the Buses Bill will require data on routes, timetables, punctuality and fares to be published; and whether this format will differ from the format currently used by his Department to publish bus fares information.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","31967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483212","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Buses Bill will include powers to require, through secondary legislation, the release of open data on fares. The specific format of the fares data will be determined following discussions with industry in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The department publishes the local bus fares index, available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387116/bus0415.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387116/bus0415.xls</a>. The bus fares index is compiled from data provided by a representative sample of around 100 operators and Transport for London.</p><p> </p><p>The department frequently reviews the statistics it produces in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. Following the Buses Bill and discussions with industry, the department will make sure the statistics it collects in relation to local bus fares continue to meet user needs.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T13:41:17.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483212/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483212/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Bus Services: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to collect and publish data on bus fares by local authority; and if he will plan for that data to include fares information in prices rather than according to the retail prices index.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","31971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483213","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>Any specific project that may bring such benefits to passengers is assessed during the planning stage of that project.</p><p> </p><p>I completely understand your concern about the cost of some rail fares and the impact that this can have on people’s budgets. That is why we have capped the rail fares we regulate at inflation (RPI) for three years running, and will continue to do so for the life of this parliament. We have also stopped operators increasing individual fares by up to 2% more. This means those fares we regulate will only rise by 1% in 2016 making it the lowest fare increase since 2010.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-24T13:05:47.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483213/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483213/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Great Western Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessments his Department has made of the potential economic benefit of (a) opening new stations on the Great Western Main line, (b) running later services on the Great Western Main line and (c) reducing rail fares on the Great Western Main line.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","31988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483214","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>Ministers regularly meet with Network Rail and the train operating companies to discuss a range of issues, including the need to ensure that the investment programme to enhance the network results in the minimum necessary disruption to passengers.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-24T10:05:11.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483214/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483214/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with (a) Network Rail and (b) train operating companies on minimising disruption from the planned closure of the Severn Tunnel for electrification.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","31942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483215","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The timings of the review of free-flow tolling have yet to be decided, and will depend on the complexity of the options to be assessed, including the details of payment collection and enforcement.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T11:21:53.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483215/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483215/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 1.274 of Budget 2016, what plans the Government has made for the timetable of the review of the case for free-flow tolling on the Severn River Crossings.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","32001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483216","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The timing and format of the consultation is yet to be decided.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T11:54:04.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483216/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483216/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 1.274 of Budget 2016, when the Government plans to consult on the tolls on the Severn River Crossings; and what (a) the aims and (b) the format of that consultation will be.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","32002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483217","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The current tolls are set not just to cover maintenance and operation costs but also to repay the construction and financing costs of the Second Severn Crossing, plus the outstanding debt on the original Crossing.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T11:16:09.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483217/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483217/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an estimate of the level of maintenance only toll on the Severn River Crossings.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","31949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483218","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Chancellor announced at Budget 2015 that the Government will abolish Category 2 tolls (small goods vehicles and small buses) and include those vehicles in Category 1, to reduce costs for businesses once Severn River Crossings are in public ownership.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-24T11:11:19.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483218/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/483218/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-21","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans that the toll level for Vehicle Category 1 and Vehicle Category 2 will be equal when the Severn Bridges return to public ownership.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","31948"
